\title{alloy: A Unified Modeling Framework for Regression and Classification}
\description{
\code{alloy} provides a single, consistent interface for fitting, displaying and
comparing a wide range of statistical and machine-learning models.  The
modeler specifies \emph{what} model they want (e.g. \code{"logit"}, \code{"weibull"},
\code{"randomForest"}) rather than \emph{how} to call the underlying function –
the package handles the rest.
}
\section{Main function}{

The entry point is \code{\link{fitMod}}, which accepts a standard R formula
and a \code{fitfn} argument naming the model type.  When \code{fitfn} is omitted the
appropriate method is chosen automatically from the response variable type.

Supported model families:
\describe{
\item{Continuous outcome}{\code{lm}, \code{lmrob}, \code{gamma}, \code{tobit}}
\item{Binary outcome}{\code{logit}}
\item{Count outcome}{\code{poisson}, \code{quasipoisson}, \code{negbin}, \code{zeroinfl}}
\item{Ordered / nominal outcome}{\code{polr}, \code{multinom}}
\item{Survival outcome}{\code{coxph}, \code{weibull}, \code{exponential},
\code{lognormal}, \code{loglogistic}}
\item{Mixed models}{\code{lmMixed}, \code{logitMixed}, \code{poissonMixed},
\code{negbinMixed}, \code{gammaMixed}}
\item{Machine learning}{\code{randomForest}, \code{nnet}, \code{rpart}, \code{C5.0},
\code{svm}, \code{naiveBayes}, \code{lda}, \code{qda}, \code{glmnet}, \code{xgboost}}
}
}

\section{Unified output}{

\code{\link{print.FitMod}} produces Stata-style output with confidence
intervals, p-values, and reference category headers, consistently across
all model types.  The \code{output} argument controls the scale:
\code{"coef"}, \code{"or"}, \code{"irr"}, \code{"hr"}, \code{"tr"},
or \code{"genuine"} (original model output).

\code{\link{predict.FitMod}} returns a numeric vector for regression and
survival models, and a tidy \code{data.frame} for classifiers
(\code{output = "prob"}, \code{"class"}, or \code{"both"}).
}

